The German word "Prolog" translates to "Prologue" in English. It refers to an introductory section or chapter that comes before the main body of a book, film, or other work.
"Come on, please!" pleaded Queen Eirwen, "Don't send her away! She's still a child!" The Ice King, accompanied by his royal advisor, looked down from his throne at his wife. She had given birth to a girl. At the thought of it, his expression darkened.
The girl resembled her mother very much. She had pale blue eyes and white hair with blue strands. To the Ice King, a girl meant weakness, as he had only produced sons up to this point.
"You have two options: Either you kill the child or you send it into the wilderness. This is his punishment for your failure, Eirwen." He spat her name out as if it were poisonous. He always did that.
Frostfell was not always a single kingdom. Earlier, it consisted of two parts, the North and the South. The North was the non-magical kingdom, while the South was a realm filled with fantastic powers. But the North showed its greed, and a never-ending war broke out between the two kingdoms, until the South eventually offered a ceasefire.
The despair in the south was so great that the royal family was willing to offer anything to put an end to the bloodshed. They proposed sending their only princess as Queen to the north, where she would bear a son, the future king. In this case, the north and the south would unite into one kingdom. The north accepted the proposal, and Princess Eirwen married Prince Akull.
"I pray of you, my king, do with me as you will, lock me up, banish me, or kill me, but spare my child," pleaded Queen Eirwen, holding her child in her arms.
The Ice King looked down on his queen with disgust. Perhaps, maybe just maybe, he would show her mercy. With the woman he had been married to for 22 years, who had stood by him through his worst times and who had given him his sons.
"Fine. The child can stay in the palace," he said, which was acknowledged by the queen with a sigh. "But," he added, "you will be executed."
The royal advisor and Queen Eirwen looked horrified at each other. Slowly, she turned her gaze to the ground. "Yes, my King." She bowed.
The Ice King ordered the royal advisor to bring the Queen's daughter into one of Eirwen's vacant chambers. Then he commanded the guards to bring Eirwen to the execution site, where all the city's citizens could watch.
While the guards escorted them to the execution site, there was a loud uprising among the citizens as they realized their only beloved queen was to be executed. Some people wept, others screamed and attacked the guards. Still others wondered why this was happening, but all were in agreement.
"The let her go!" or "Let her be!"
"Why do they do that to her?"
As Eirwen approached the wooden stake, the most feared person in the kingdom appeared. The Executioner. The woman who had just been queen was to be burned. No one deserved such a death, not even criminals. It was the worst that could be done to a person in Frostfell.
Eirwen was bound to the wooden stake, and the king declared in a speech how the queen had betrayed them all. The inhabitants of Frostfell refused to believe the king and would not accept his words. Then, the executioner lit the wooden stake on fire, and a single tear rolled down the former queen's face.
"Don't give up, Kari." This was the end of Queen Eirwen's reign.
Dead silence in the palace
Only a knocking could be heard from the room located all the way to the far left in the South wing of the eternally cold palace. The servants who passed by always wondered what was contained within that room. They were afraid of it. Rumors circulated among the maidservants around the palace. Allegedly, the late Queen of the Ice King, Eirwen, was in that room and waiting to be released.
Your guess could not have been more wrong, thought Ivory, and she walked towards the South Wing while the servants wandered about, whispering to each other. They had no idea what was hidden behind the door.
The rumors also naturally concerned Ivory, as she was the only one allowed to enter the room.
Knock, knock. "Lady Kari, are you in there?" whispered Ivory before the door, which was adorned with snowflakes and a crown, the symbol of the royal family.
Ivory wondered if, unlike the last attempt, she would actually be granted entry. I still have bruises from last time. Ivory giggled at the thought. Kari had thrown a book at Ivory's shoulder, but immediately apologized when she realized who she had hit.
A single knock came from inside, presumably to say that she was there. Where else could she be?
"May I come in?" asked Ivory. Earlier, Ivory would enter without asking.
From within, Ivory heard a knocking. This likely meant a "Yes." The cold and the noise made Ivory shiver. It felt strange to hear a sound from what was supposedly an empty room, even though Ivory had been entering it for several years.
"I come in," said Ivory and opened the door slowly. The sight that greeted Ivory in the room was unusual for normal people, but not unexpected for her. Papers were scattered everywhere. Books were strewn about, the desk was broken, and several ice sculptures were lying around. There were no windows, and there was little to no light. Additionally, it was colder than in the rest of the palace (which said quite a lot). The room looked as though a snowstorm had swept through it.
The girl lay curled up in her bed, wrapped in her blanket, and was reading in one of her notebooks. A small lantern illuminated the room.
"Which notebook is this?" asked Ivory and sat down next to Kari on the bed.
